name: 7-Bromoquinolin-8-ol
Reason: The base structure for this compound can be considered to be quinoline, which itself is derived from the fusion of a benzene ring to a pyridine ring. Quinoline has a melting point of around 23°C. Adding a hydroxyl group (a phenol derivative) to the compound generally increases the melting point due to the ability to form hydrogen bonds, which increases the intermolecular forces and thus requires more energy to melt the compound. The hydroxyl group could increase the melting point by approximately +80°C. The bromo group also increases the melting point due to the increased molecular weight and the slight increase in polarizability, which can increase dispersion forces between molecules; this could add another +30°C to the melting point. Combining these increments, the overall increase compared to quinoline would be around +110°C, which would predict a melting point of 23+110=133°C for 7-bromoquinolin-8-ol.
